Introduction: Describing Data

We are interested in exploring the relationship between the two variables âGDP per capitaâ and âTotal Fertility Rateâ. We retrieved datasets on these two variables from Gapminder.org.

The dataset gdp.csv contains the gross domestic product (GDP) per person (capita) for 195 countries from 1800 to 2100, with each year a column (variable) and each country a row (observation). GDP per capita âmeasures the value of everything produced in a country during a year, divided by the number of peopleâ (Gapminder). The unit is international dollars, fixed to 2017 prices adjusted for inflation and differences in cost of living, known as PPP dollars. Although flawed, GDP per capita is often used as a core indicator of a countryâs economic performance and average living standards. Gapminderâs dataset has predicted data up to 2100 using forecasts and predictive modeling. However, for the scope of our project, we will focus on data up to 2024.

The dataset children.csv contains the number of babies per woman (Total Fertility Rate) for 202 countries from 1800 to 2100, with each year a column (variable) and each country a row (observation). Total Fertility Rate is âthe number of children that would be born to each woman with prevailing age-specific fertility ratesâ (Gapminder). Gapminderâs dataset uses estimates from the UN for most of its data and has predicted data up to 2100 using the UN projection of future fertility rate in all countries. However, for the scope of our project, we will focus on data up to 2024.

We hypothesize that there will be a negative association between GDP per capita and Total Fertility Rate. Our explanatory variable will be GDP per capita and our response variable of interest will be Total Fertility Rate. Through internet research, we found that, in general, poor countries tend to have higher levels of fertility than rich countries (Vandenbroucke). We are interested in exploring and confirming (or refuting) this relationship in general and over time with the time series data that we have.

Cleaning Data

To prepare our data for analysis, we pivoted each dataset to long format to get the year to be a single column. We converted the year variable to numeric and filtered the data to only include years up to 2024. For the gdp.csv dataset we had to convert all âkâ values (i.e.Â â90kâ) to numeric and multiply by 1000. We also dropped all NA values in both datasets. Then, we merged both datasets using an inner_join() to only contain observations that have values for both gdp and fertility.

Cleaning fertility.csv

Code 
fertility_long <- fertility |>
  pivot_longer(cols = c("1800":"2100"),
               names_to = "year",
               values_to = "fertility") |>
  mutate(year = as.numeric(year)) |>
  filter(year < 2025) |>
  drop_na()

Cleaning gdp.csv

Code 
gdp_long <- gdp |>
  mutate(across(c("1800":"2100"), 
                ~ifelse(str_detect(.x, "k"), 
                        as.numeric(str_replace_all(.x, "k", ""))*1000,
                        as.numeric(.x)))) |>
  pivot_longer(cols = c("1800":"2100"),
               names_to = "year",
               values_to = "gdp") |>
  mutate(year = as.numeric(year)) |>
  filter(year < 2025) |>
  drop_na()

Combining both datasets

Our final cleaned and merged dataset fertility_gdp has 4 variables: country (character), year (numeric), gdp (numeric), and fertility (numeric). It contains data on 186 countries in total from the years 1800-2024.

Code 
fertility_gdp <- gdp_long |>
  inner_join(fertility_long)

2 Linear Regression

2.1 Data Visualization

We will begin by investigating visualization of data on Gross Domestic Product and Fertility rate. Firstly, we investigate the relationship of Gross Domestic Product over time and Fertility rate over time. We average GDP and fertility across all countries per year, to get a single value for average GDP and average Fertility Rate for every year. We also normalized the values of GDP and fertility rate to be between 0 and 1, so that we can compare the two variables with each other, in the following graphic.

Code 
rescale_01 <- function(x){
  stopifnot(is.numeric(x))
  stopifnot(length(x) > 1)
  
  min = min(x, na.rm = TRUE)
  max = max(x, na.rm = TRUE)
  
  return ( (x-min)/(max-min) )
}

avg_fertility_gdp <-fertility_gdp |>
  #filter(country == "USA") |> #keep this line to see the USA (baby-boom)
  group_by(year) |>
  summarize(mean_gdp = mean(gdp), 
            mean_fertility = mean(fertility)) |>
  mutate(gdp_normalized = rescale_01(mean_gdp),
         fertility_normalized = rescale_01(mean_fertility))

ggplot(avg_fertility_gdp, aes(x = year)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = gdp_normalized, color = "GDP"), linetype="dashed") +
  geom_line(aes(y = fertility_normalized, color = "Fertility"))+
  labs(title = "Normalized Mean Global Fertility Rate and GDP over Years",
      y=NULL,
      subtitle = "Normalized Mean Global Fertility Rate and GDP",
      x = "Year",
      color="Variable")

As we can see from the visualization, from 1800 to the roughly mid-1920s, GDP and Fertility rate were fairly stable, with Fertility Rate being higher than GDP. Around 1925, the fertility rate started to drop, with a steep decline in the 1960s, and a consistent decrease since then. As for GDP, it also started to rise around the 1920s and almost exponentially increased around the 1950s. The two variables seem to be inversely related over time; as Fertility Rate falls, GDP increases.

Next, we visualize the relationship of the two variables between each other. Here, we average the GDP and Fertility rate across time, to get a single value for average GDP and average Fertility Rate for each country in our dataset.

Code 
avg_fertility_gdp <- fertility_gdp |>
  group_by(country)|>
  summarise(avg_fertility = mean(fertility), avg_gdp = mean(gdp)) 
  
ggplot(aes(x = avg_gdp,
             y = avg_fertility),
       data = avg_fertility_gdp) +
  geom_point()+
  labs(title = "Average Fertility Rate vs Average GDP per country",
       subtitle = "Average Fertility Rate per Country (# of babies per woman)",
       y = NULL,
       x = "Average GDP per Country (2017 PPP$)")+
  theme_bw()

In this graph, we can see that as average GDP increases, the average Fertility rate tends to decrease. We can also see that the majority of the countries have an average GDP under 10,000 and an average fertility rate above 4. There seems to be an evident negative relationship. However there may be some curvature indicating a negative exponential form. Additionally, the relationship is not very strong as the data points at increased average GDP values are more spread out.

2.2 Linear Regression

In this exploration, we will create a simple linear regression model to attempt to fit our data. Simple Linear regression assumes a linear relationship between the variables, average GDP and average Fertility rate, as well as normally distributed, independent errors with a mean of 0 and equal variance.

First, we will analyze the Linear Regression assumptions.

Linearity Assumptions

From our plot of average GDP vs.Â average Fertility Rate in section 2.1, we can see that the data may not follow a linear relationship. The form of the observations seems to be more curved, and therefore the linearity assumption may be violated.

Independence Assumptions

Whether our errors are independent of each other depends on the sampling method of the data. Here we assume that the data from Gapminder was randomly sampled, and therefore the independence assumption is met.

Normal Distribution of Errors

To assess the distribution of our errors we look at the following plot

Code 
errors <- resid(model)

Code 
error_df <- data.frame(Errors = errors)

Code 
error_df|>
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = Errors)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  labs(y = "",
       x = "Residuals",
       title = "Histogram of Residuals")+
  theme_bw()
Error in eval(expr, envir, enclos): object 'error_df' not found

This plot somewhat resembles a bell-curve. There are a few values that are unusually large, and they may be outliers. Nonetheless, we can conclude that the normality assumption is reasonably met.

Equal Variance

To assess the variance of our errors, we look at the following plot;

Code 
model |>
  augment()|>
  ggplot(aes(x = .fitted, 
             y=.resid)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Fitted Values",
       y = NULL,
       subtitle = "Residual Values",
       title = "Residuals vs. Fitted Plot")+
  theme_bw()
Error in eval(expr, envir, enclos): object 'model' not found

In this plot of fitted values versus residuals, we can see some fanning in the data points. This indicates that the equal variance assumption is violated. Due to this violation, we will be cautious as we perform simple linear regression.

After fitting the data, the estimated linear regression model is as follows:

Code 
model <- lm(avg_fertility ~ avg_gdp, data = avg_fertility_gdp)
tidy(model) |>
knitr::kable(digits = 2)
term estimate std.error statistic p.value
(Intercept) 5.98 0.09 64.61 0
avg_gdp 0.00 0.00 -9.97 0

\(\widehat{Average Fertility}=5.9839-0.00012(AverageGDP)\)

Coefficient Interpretations

The estimated intercept of the model was 5.9839. When the countryâs average GDP over the years 1800 to 2024 is equal to zero, the countryâs estimated average fertility rate is 5.9839 babies per woman.

The estimated slope coefficient for Average GDP was -0.00012. For every $1 (in PPP 2017 dollars) increase in countryâs average GDP, the countryâs estimated average fertility rate is estimated to decrease by 0.00012 babies per woman. Equivalently, for every $10,000 (in PPP 2017 dollars) increase in countryâs average GDP the countryâs estimated average fertility rate is estimated to decrease by 1.2 babies per woman.

Assessing Model Fit

As for assessing the fit of our model, we can refer to the following table of variances:

Code 
variances <- data.frame(
  response_variance = var(avg_fertility_gdp$avg_fertility),
  fitted_variance = var(model$fitted.values),
  residual_variance = var(model$residuals)
)

variances |>
knitr::kable(digits = 2)
response_variance fitted_variance residual_variance
1.18 0.41 0.76

This table shows that about 0.414/1.179 = 0.351, or about 35.1% of the variability in the average fertility rate values was accounted for by our regression model. This is a somewhat low amount of variability being explained, as there is about 0.765/1.179 = 0.649, or about 64.9% of variability in the response still left unexplained by the model with only average GDP as the predictor.

Considering how many factors influence Fertility rate overall, being able to explain 35.1% of its variability is somewhat impressive. Still, only looking at R-squared, our simple linear regression model with average GDP as the predictor is not ideal. The remaining variability could be explained with a more complex model that looks at other factors influencing Fertility rate.

3 Simulation

We will now generate a predictive check, to assess how well our model is performing. We simulate data from our linear regression model and then compare this to the actual observed data points, reporting the proportion of variability explained.

3.1 Visualizing Simulation from the Model

In the following graphic, we visualize a single simulation of data from our model next to the actual observations.

Code 
set.seed(100)

pred <- predict(model)
rse <- sigma(model)

noise <- function (x, sd){
  x + rnorm(length(x), mean = 0, sd)
  
}

predicted_er <- noise(pred, rse)

data <- data.frame(avg_gdp = avg_fertility_gdp$avg_gdp, pred_er = predicted_er)

data_both <- data.frame(
  avg_gdp = avg_fertility_gdp$avg_gdp,
  pred_fertility = predicted_er,
  avg_fertility = avg_fertility_gdp$avg_fertility)

plot_pred <- ggplot(data = data_both, aes(x = avg_gdp)) +

geom_point(aes(y = predicted_er), color = "darkseagreen3", shape=1) + 
  labs(title = "Simulated Data",
       x = "Average GDP (2017 PPP$)",
       y = NULL,
       subtitle = "Average Fertiltiy Rate (# of babies per woman)") +
  theme_bw()


plot_obs <- ggplot(data = data_both, aes(x = avg_gdp)) +
geom_point(aes(y = avg_fertility), color = "slateblue", shape=8) + 
    labs(title = "Observed Data",
       x = "Average GDP (2017 PPP$)",
       y = NULL,
       subtitle = "Average Fertiltiy Rate (# of babies per woman)") +
  theme_bw()

plot_combined <- plot_pred + plot_obs
plot_combined

From this graphic, we can see that our simulated data differs from our observed data. Both graphs have a negative association and are right skewed. However, our simulated data follows a much more linear association than our observed. Again, the observed data follows a more curved association, with a couple potential outliers in the upper right corner of the graph.

3.2 Generating Multiple Predictive Checks

Next, we perform the same comparison as above 1000 times and report the proportion of variability explained in the observed data by our simulated data. Then, we can plot a distribution of this amount of variability explained across the 1000 simulations. This distribution is shown below.

Code 
set.seed(222)
model_lm <- lm(avg_fertility ~ avg_gdp, data = avg_fertility_gdp)
model_predict <- predict(model_lm)
model_sigma <- sigma(model_lm)
noise <- function(x, mean = 0, sd){
  x + rnorm(length(x), 
            mean, 
            sd)
}
sim_response <- tibble(sim_fertility = noise(model_predict,
                                             sd = model_sigma))
sim_data <- avg_fertility_gdp |>
  filter(!is.na(avg_fertility),
         !is.na(avg_gdp)) |>
  select(avg_fertility, avg_gdp) |>
  bind_cols(sim_response)

lm(avg_fertility ~ sim_fertility, data = sim_data) |>
  glance()

Code 
sim_r2 <- lm(avg_fertility ~sim_fertility, data = sim_data) |>
  glance() |>
  select(r.squared) |>
  pull()

sims <- map_dfc(.x = 1:1000,
                .f = ~tibble(sim = noise(model_predict,
                                         sd = model_sigma)))
colnames(sims) <- colnames(sims) |> 
  str_replace(pattern = "\\.\\.\\.",
                  replace = "_")

sims <- avg_fertility_gdp |>
  filter(!is.na(avg_fertility),
         !is.na(avg_gdp)) |>
  select(avg_fertility) |>
  bind_cols(sims)

sims_r_squared <- sims |>
  map( ~ lm(avg_fertility ~ .x, data=sims)) |>
  map(glance) |>
  map_dbl(~.x$r.squared)

sims_r_squared <- sims_r_squared[names(sims_r_squared) != "avg_fertility"]

tibble(sims = sims_r_squared) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = sims)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.025) +
  labs(x = "Simulated R^2",
       y= NULL,
       subtitle = "Number of Simulated Models",
       title = "Distribution of simulated R^2") +
  theme_bw()

## Introduction: Describing Data

We are interested in exploring the relationship between the two variables âGDP per capitaâ and âTotal Fertility Rateâ. We retrieved datasets on these two variables from Gapminder.org.

The dataset `gdp.csv` contains the gross domestic product (GDP) per person (capita) for 195 countries from 1800 to 2100, with each year a column (variable) and each country a row (observation). GDP per capita âmeasures the value of everything produced in a country during a year, divided by the number of peopleâ (Gapminder). The unit is international dollars, fixed to 2017 prices adjusted for inflation and differences in cost of living, known as PPP dollars. Although flawed, GDP per capita is often used as a core indicator of a countryâs economic performance and average living standards. Gapminderâs dataset has predicted data up to 2100 [using forecasts and predictive modeling](https://www.gapminder.org/data/documentation/gd001/). However, for the scope of our project, we will focus on data up to 2024.

The dataset `children.csv` contains the number of babies per woman (Total Fertility Rate) for 202 countries from 1800 to 2100, with each year a column (variable) and each country a row (observation). Total Fertility Rate is âthe number of children that would be born to each woman with prevailing age-specific fertility ratesâ (Gapminder). Gapminderâs dataset uses estimates from the UN for most of its data and has predicted data up to 2100 using the UN projection of future fertility rate in all countries. However, for the scope of our project, we will focus on data up to 2024.

We hypothesize that there will be a **negative** association between GDP per capita and Total Fertility Rate. Our explanatory variable will be GDP per capita and our response variable of interest will be Total Fertility Rate. Through internet research, we found that, in general, poor countries tend to have higher levels of fertility than rich countries ([Vandenbroucke](https://www.stlouisfed.org/on-the-economy/2016/december/link-fertility-income)). We are interested in exploring and confirming (or refuting) this relationship in general and over time with the time series data that we have.


## Cleaning Data

To prepare our data for analysis, we pivoted each dataset to long format to get the year to be a single column. We converted the `year` variable to numeric and filtered the data to only include years up to 2024. For the `gdp.csv` dataset we had to convert all âkâ values (i.e. "90k") to numeric and multiply by 1000. We also dropped all NA values in both datasets. Then, we merged both datasets using an inner_join() to only contain observations that have values for both gdp and fertility.

### Cleaning `fertility.csv`

```{r}
#| code-fold: TRUE
fertility_long <- fertility |>
  pivot_longer(cols = c("1800":"2100"),
               names_to = "year",
               values_to = "fertility") |>
  mutate(year = as.numeric(year)) |>
  filter(year < 2025) |>
  drop_na()
```

### Cleaning `gdp.csv`

```{r}
#| code-fold: TRUE
gdp_long <- gdp |>
  mutate(across(c("1800":"2100"), 
                ~ifelse(str_detect(.x, "k"), 
                        as.numeric(str_replace_all(.x, "k", ""))*1000,
                        as.numeric(.x)))) |>
  pivot_longer(cols = c("1800":"2100"),
               names_to = "year",
               values_to = "gdp") |>
  mutate(year = as.numeric(year)) |>
  filter(year < 2025) |>
  drop_na()
```

### Combining both datasets

Our final cleaned and merged dataset `fertility_gdp` has 4 variables: country (character), year (numeric), gdp (numeric), and fertility (numeric). It contains data on 186 countries in total from the years 1800-2024.

```{r}
#| code-fold: TRUE
fertility_gdp <- gdp_long |>
  inner_join(fertility_long)
```

### Independence Assumptions
Whether our errors are independent of each other depends on the sampling method of the data. Here we assume that the data from Gapminder was randomly sampled, and therefore the independence assumption is met.

### Coefficient Interpretations

The estimated intercept of the model was 5.9839. When the country's average GDP over the years 1800 to 2024 is equal to zero, the country's estimated average fertility rate is 5.9839 babies per woman.

The estimated slope coefficient for Average GDP was -0.00012. For every \$1 (in PPP 2017 dollars) increase in country's average GDP, the country's estimated average fertility rate is estimated to decrease by 0.00012 babies per woman. Equivalently, for every \$10,000 (in PPP 2017 dollars) increase in country's average GDP the country's estimated average fertility rate is estimated to decrease by 1.2 babies per woman.

### Assessing Model Fit
As for assessing the fit of our model, we can refer to the following table of variances:

```{r}
#| code-fold: true
variances <- data.frame(
  response_variance = var(avg_fertility_gdp$avg_fertility),
  fitted_variance = var(model$fitted.values),
  residual_variance = var(model$residuals)
)

variances |>
knitr::kable(digits = 2)
```

This table shows that about 0.414/1.179 = 0.351, or about 35.1% of the variability in the average fertility rate values was accounted for by our regression model. This is a somewhat low amount of variability being explained, as there is about 0.765/1.179 = 0.649, or about 64.9% of variability in the response still left unexplained by the model with only average GDP as the predictor.

Considering how many factors influence Fertility rate overall, being able to explain 35.1% of its variability is somewhat impressive. Still, only looking at R-squared, our simple linear regression model with average GDP as the predictor is not ideal. The remaining variability could be explained with a more complex model that looks at other factors influencing Fertility rate.


# 3 Simulation

We will now generate a predictive check, to assess how well our model is performing. We simulate data from our linear regression model and then compare this to the actual observed data points, reporting the proportion of variability explained. 

## 3.1 Visualizing Simulation from the Model

In the following graphic, we visualize a single simulation of data from our model next to the actual observations.
```{r}
#| code-fold: true
set.seed(100)

pred <- predict(model)
rse <- sigma(model)

noise <- function (x, sd){
  x + rnorm(length(x), mean = 0, sd)
  
}

predicted_er <- noise(pred, rse)

data <- data.frame(avg_gdp = avg_fertility_gdp$avg_gdp, pred_er = predicted_er)

data_both <- data.frame(
  avg_gdp = avg_fertility_gdp$avg_gdp,
  pred_fertility = predicted_er,
  avg_fertility = avg_fertility_gdp$avg_fertility)

plot_pred <- ggplot(data = data_both, aes(x = avg_gdp)) +

geom_point(aes(y = predicted_er), color = "darkseagreen3", shape=1) + 
  labs(title = "Simulated Data",
       x = "Average GDP (2017 PPP$)",
       y = NULL,
       subtitle = "Average Fertiltiy Rate (# of babies per woman)") +
  theme_bw()


plot_obs <- ggplot(data = data_both, aes(x = avg_gdp)) +
geom_point(aes(y = avg_fertility), color = "slateblue", shape=8) + 
    labs(title = "Observed Data",
       x = "Average GDP (2017 PPP$)",
       y = NULL,
       subtitle = "Average Fertiltiy Rate (# of babies per woman)") +
  theme_bw()

plot_combined <- plot_pred + plot_obs
plot_combined

```
From this graphic, we can see that our simulated data differs from our observed data. Both graphs have a negative association and are right skewed. However, our simulated data follows a much more linear association than our observed. Again, the observed data follows a more curved association, with a couple potential outliers in the upper right corner of the graph.

## 3.2 Generating Multiple Predictive Checks

Next, we perform the same comparison as above 1000 times and report the proportion of variability explained in the observed data by our simulated data. Then, we can plot a distribution of this amount of variability explained across the 1000 simulations. This distribution is shown below.

```{r}
#| code-fold: true
set.seed(222)
model_lm <- lm(avg_fertility ~ avg_gdp, data = avg_fertility_gdp)
model_predict <- predict(model_lm)
model_sigma <- sigma(model_lm)
noise <- function(x, mean = 0, sd){
  x + rnorm(length(x), 
            mean, 
            sd)
}
sim_response <- tibble(sim_fertility = noise(model_predict,
                                             sd = model_sigma))
sim_data <- avg_fertility_gdp |>
  filter(!is.na(avg_fertility),
         !is.na(avg_gdp)) |>
  select(avg_fertility, avg_gdp) |>
  bind_cols(sim_response)

lm(avg_fertility ~ sim_fertility, data = sim_data) |>
  glance()

sim_r2 <- lm(avg_fertility ~sim_fertility, data = sim_data) |>
  glance() |>
  select(r.squared) |>
  pull()

sims <- map_dfc(.x = 1:1000,
                .f = ~tibble(sim = noise(model_predict,
                                         sd = model_sigma)))
colnames(sims) <- colnames(sims) |> 
  str_replace(pattern = "\\.\\.\\.",
                  replace = "_")

sims <- avg_fertility_gdp |>
  filter(!is.na(avg_fertility),
         !is.na(avg_gdp)) |>
  select(avg_fertility) |>
  bind_cols(sims)

sims_r_squared <- sims |>
  map( ~ lm(avg_fertility ~ .x, data=sims)) |>
  map(glance) |>
  map_dbl(~.x$r.squared)

sims_r_squared <- sims_r_squared[names(sims_r_squared) != "avg_fertility"]

tibble(sims = sims_r_squared) |>
  ggplot(aes(x = sims)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.025) +
  labs(x = "Simulated R^2",
       y= NULL,
       subtitle = "Number of Simulated Models",
       title = "Distribution of simulated R^2") +
  theme_bw()
```
